When key is created:
store expiry_time = now + ttl

During reads:
if current_time > expiry_time
    key considered expired

This check is cheap.

To avoid keeping expired keys forever:
background cleanup jobs periodically delete them.

This combines:
1. Lazy expiration during reads
2. Periodic cleanup in background



Soft delete (is_expired) usually unnecessary because:

expiry_time already tells whether expired
extra column increases storage/indexing



Real systems like Redis do:

1. Passive Expiration
Check expiry during read.

2. Active Expiration
Background thread randomly scans and deletes expired keys.



